version: 1
display_name: VCFO-9X-000106 - The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations for Networks Platform NGINX server must configure the Referrer-Policy header.
global_description: |-
  A Referrer header may expose sensitive data in another web server's log if you use sensitive data in your URL parameters, such as personal information, username, and password or persistent sessions. Ultimately, depending on your application design, not using a properly configured Referrer Policy may allow session hijacking, credential gathering, or sensitive data exposure in a third party's logs.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFO-9X-000106
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000516-WSR-000174
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_operations_net_nginx:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations for Networks Platform NGINX server must configure the Referrer-Policy header.
    control_id: VCFO-9X-000106
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      Verify a header is configured to set a Referrer-Policy.

      View the running configuration by running the following command:

      # nginx -T 2>&1 | sed -n "/^http\s{/,/server\s{/p" | grep add_header

      Example configuration:

      server {
      add_header Referrer-Policy "no-referrer";
      }

      If a header is not configured as shown in the example in the http, server, or location context, this is a finding.

      Note: There can be several add_header directives. These directives are inherited from the previous configuration level if and only if there are no add_header directives defined on the current level so care must be taken if add_header is defined at multiple levels to include headers configured at a higher level.
    rationale: |-
      A Referrer header may expose sensitive data in another web server's log if you use sensitive data in your URL parameters, such as personal information, username, and password or persistent sessions. Ultimately, depending on your application design, not using a properly configured Referrer Policy may allow session hijacking, credential gathering, or sensitive data exposure in a third party's logs.
    remediation: |-
      Navigate to and open:

      The /etc/nginx/sites-available/vnera file.

      Add or update the "add_header Referrer-Policy" directive for each of the server contexts, for example:

      server {
      listen 443 ssl http2;

      add_header Referrer-Policy "no-referrer";
      }

      Reload the NGINX configuration by running the following command:

      # nginx -s reload

      Note: There can be several add_header directives. These directives are inherited from the previous configuration level if and only if there are no add_header directives defined on the current level so care must be taken if add_header is defined at multiple levels to include headers configured at a higher level.
